<div id="review_2621186374" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2621186374" />
    <a title="Sally Boyer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5899702-sally-boyer"><img alt="Sally Boyer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620789025p2/5899702.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2621186374?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sally Boyer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sally Boyer" href="/user/show/5899702-sally-boyer">Sally Boyer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2621186374&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2621186374" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5473476812739215818">I don’t read much poetry, but this book has convinced me to start. Several of the poems made me think of my mother, and that was a sweet, nostalgic feeling. <br/><br/>Some excerpts from the two poems I especially loved:<br/><br/>The Night, The Porch<br/><br/>To stare at nothing is to learn by heart<br/>What all of us will be swept into, and baring oneself<br/>To the wind is feeling the ungraspable somewhere close by. <br/>Trees can sway or be still. Day or night can be what they wish. <br/>...<br/><br/>What It Was <br/><br/>II<br/><br/>...<br/>The ruined moonlight fell across he</span>
  <span id="freeText5473476812739215818" style="display:none">I don’t read much poetry, but this book has convinced me to start. Several of the poems made me think of my mother, and that was a sweet, nostalgic feeling. <br /><br />Some excerpts from the two poems I especially loved:<br /><br />The Night, The Porch<br /><br />To stare at nothing is to learn by heart<br />What all of us will be swept into, and baring oneself<br />To the wind is feeling the ungraspable somewhere close by. <br />Trees can sway or be still. Day or night can be what they wish. <br />...<br /><br />What It Was <br /><br />II<br /><br />...<br />The ruined moonlight fell across her hair.<br />... the shore/littered with stars. <br />It was the sun on my hand. It was the sun’s heat. It was the way<br />I sat, the way I waited for hours, for days....<br /><br /><br />Many of the lines in the poems were striking as well:<br /><br />“...watching/The ancient moon creep across the floor.” (The Beach House)<br /><br />“Nobody sees it happening, but the architecture of our time/Is becoming the architecture of the next time.” (The Next Time)<br /><br />“And you think that perhaps you are not who you thought...” (A Suite of Appearances, III)<br /><br />“And day and night were one/And the sea’s green body was near.” (The Delirium Waltz)<br /><br />Finally, the final verse of the last entry of the Delirium Waltz, something worthy of memorization: <br /><br />“And the rush of water was loud as if the ballroom were flooded. And I was dancing alone in the absence of all that I knew and was bound by. And here was the sea—the blur, the erasure of difference, the end of self, the end of whatever surrounds the self. And I kept going. The breakers flashed and fell under the moon’s gaze. Scattered petals of foam shone briefly, then sank in the sand. It was cold, and I found myself suddenly back with the others. That vast ungraspable body, the sea, that huge and meaningless empire of water, was left on its own.” </span>
  <a data-text-id="5473476812739215818" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
