    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_471787556" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/471787556" />
    <a title="Avery Taylor" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15248123-avery-taylor"><img alt="Avery Taylor" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/471787556?book_show_action=true">Dec 06, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Avery Taylor" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Avery Taylor" href="/user/show/15248123-avery-taylor">Avery Taylor</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer471787556" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14147330859265337845">From the brilliant and unmatched Mark Strand, “Blizzard of One” is yet another masterpiece of the English language, a votive candle to a strange and restless sense of the world we live in. This collection leaves an impression of both timelessness and nostalgia at once, a collection of poems with surprisingly ordinary language, spun into transcendent works of peace and anger and love.<br/><br/>From the poem “A Piece of the Storm”, the work that lends the collection its title, which has a sense of restlessn</span>
  <span id="freeText14147330859265337845" style="display:none">From the brilliant and unmatched Mark Strand, “Blizzard of One” is yet another masterpiece of the English language, a votive candle to a strange and restless sense of the world we live in. This collection leaves an impression of both timelessness and nostalgia at once, a collection of poems with surprisingly ordinary language, spun into transcendent works of peace and anger and love.<br /><br />From the poem “A Piece of the Storm”, the work that lends the collection its title, which has a sense of restlessness in its measured capture of time and existence, to the poem “Our Masterpiece is the Private Life” which is full of a deep stillness that paints the picture of a previous life that we, as readers, never lived but suddenly, yes, yes, we were there---“Back to the house, the sea pounding against the cliffs, / The glass of whiskey on the table, the open book, the questions…”---the impression of familiarity so strong, and then at once the sense of mystery equally strong. Strand’s gorgeous poetry is like that: full of contradictions that lead up to a peculiar blend of emotions that seem like they should not mesh as well as they do. Joy and defeat. Anxiety and rest. Peace and fury. <br /><br />There is, as with all of Mark Strand’s poetry collections, always the unexpected element of humor twined in with the serious and the solemn. In fact, it’s this humor that sort of sobers up specific parts of Strand’s writing, making everything crystal-clear and on-edge, a fierce kind of contrast between what actually is a joke and what is not.<br />Mark Strand’s matchless collection of poetry, “Blizzard of One”, surely will live a very long healthy life.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14147330859265337845" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

