  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1094024702" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1094024702" />
    <a title="Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1289730-jeffrey-akiva-savett"><img alt="Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1597028043p2/1289730.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1094024702?book_show_action=true">Oct 31, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett" href="/user/show/1289730-jeffrey-akiva-savett">Jeffrey (Akiva) Savett</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1094024702" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7178004032310507628">The review listed from the publisher here states that Strand&apos;s poetry &quot;occupies the space between abstraction and the sensuous particulars of experience.&quot; I&apos;m disappointed to say that it doesn&apos;t occupy the space BETWEEN those two binaries, Strand&apos;s poetry is quite surely in the abstract camp.<br/><br/>For me, at least, this is not a good thing. Most of my favorite poets, Ted Kooser, Galway Kinnell, Marie Howe and Jane Kenyon for instance BEGIN with the concrete, the sensuous, the world. Their imagery does</span>
  <span id="freeText7178004032310507628" style="display:none">The review listed from the publisher here states that Strand's poetry "occupies the space between abstraction and the sensuous particulars of experience." I'm disappointed to say that it doesn't occupy the space BETWEEN those two binaries, Strand's poetry is quite surely in the abstract camp.<br /><br />For me, at least, this is not a good thing. Most of my favorite poets, Ted Kooser, Galway Kinnell, Marie Howe and Jane Kenyon for instance BEGIN with the concrete, the sensuous, the world. Their imagery does the work for them and this work is not explained or hinted at. The "meaning" just simply IS the image. As Howe called it in one of her book titles, The Kingdom of Ordinary Time. Strand has been compared in his surrealism to Robert Bly, but again, I reject that comparison. Bly and Bob Hicok, and Dean Young and Charles Simic, these are my poetic heroes. Yes, their language sometimes verges on abstraction but even then, the language itself is so beautiful. I find myself spellbound. Not so here with Strand. <br /><br />There is much to enjoy in this book. I know it won the Pulitzer. There are lines that will give you goosebumps. But there are not enough and they occur too many pages apart from each other to keep me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7178004032310507628" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

