<div id="review_1850376333" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1850376333" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32853296-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1850376333?book_show_action=true">Jan 31, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/32853296-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32853296-michael?shelf=2017-to-read">2017-to-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32853296-michael?shelf=2017-completed">2017-completed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1850376333" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1974096563803268580">Strand is an interesting case, insomuch as he&apos;s been around so long that his work tends to drift through different periods. Published some 30 years after his first collection, Blizzard is a much more personalized account than his prior work. You&apos;ll find almost each poem is dedicated to a person in Strand&apos;s life (this carries it&apos;s own significance, I think.) The themes are more sweeping and grand than in prior works, too, and they seem to reflect, often enough, on the end of Strand&apos;s life. Days a</span>
  <span id="freeText1974096563803268580" style="display:none">Strand is an interesting case, insomuch as he's been around so long that his work tends to drift through different periods. Published some 30 years after his first collection, Blizzard is a much more personalized account than his prior work. You'll find almost each poem is dedicated to a person in Strand's life (this carries it's own significance, I think.) The themes are more sweeping and grand than in prior works, too, and they seem to reflect, often enough, on the end of Strand's life. Days are dreams, sunsets are validations for our lives, and the glow of moonlight is everywhere. As in all his work, Strand again proves you don't have to bury your head in the minutia all the time, and that the obvious symbol can still be beautiful when in the hands of a master. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1974096563803268580" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
